{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-post-js","path":"/palm-springs-part-3-joshua-tree/","result":{"data":{"wordpressPost":{"id":"6bf1388e-a10f-514f-a640-7aad52cc40ae","title":"Palm Springs, Part 3: Joshua Tree","slug":"palm-springs-part-3-joshua-tree","content":"<p>Fun facts about Joshua Tree National Park!</p>\n<ul>\n<li>U2&#8217;s album photographs were not from Joshua Tree National Park, but rather the band found this lone Yucca brevifolia out near Darwin, CA along Route 190, which is some 250 miles north of the park.</li>\n<li>The nearly 800,000-acre National Park is larger than the state of Rhode Island.</li>\n<li>The whole big place is zone 8a-8b.  Maybe a couple of 9a spots on the fringes (Palm Springs is 9b with a couple 10a micros).</li>\n</ul>\n<p>I&#8217;ll let you research the rest of what may be of interest; let&#8217;s get to pictures.</p>\n<p>From where we stayed in Palm Springs it took maybe 45 minutes or so to get to the west entrance of the park.  From there, we drove in (with a couple stops along the way) to Hidden Valley where we took a roughly one-mile hike.</p>\n<p>Et voilà.  The park&#8217;s namesake, Yucca brevifolia.  And indeed the leaves are indeed shorter than the familiar Y. gloriosa and Y. filamentosa and whatever else we might see more frequently.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-472\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4669-e1518727310637-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"768\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4669-e1518727310637.jpg 768w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4669-e1518727310637-225x300.jpg 225w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\" /></p>\n<p>I read somewhere that in parts of Joshua Tree, the natural plant combinations can have the look of an intentionally designed and planted garden.  Turns out that&#8217;s true! I was immediately drawn to this plant against that plant, time and time again.  It&#8217;s like <a href=\"https://oudolf.com/\" target=\"_blank\" rel=\"noopener\">Oudolf</a> was here&#8230;</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-473\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4671-e1518727592859-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"768\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4671-e1518727592859.jpg 768w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4671-e1518727592859-225x300.jpg 225w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\" /></p>\n<p>Okay, this next is just one plant but I loved it against the rocks with its excitement of flower stalks.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-474\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4673-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4673.jpg 1024w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4673-300x225.jpg 300w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4673-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>At one point, I kept noticing a very lovely honey-like fragrance, but I couldn&#8217;t see any flowers.  In fact, it seemed to emanate from this dead-looking Senegalia greggii (I think) with all the odd growths on it.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-475\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4684-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4684.jpg 1024w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4684-300x225.jpg 300w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4684-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" /></p>\n<p>Turns out those growths are indeed a different plant: Phoradendron californicum, one of the many mistletoes native to North America. See the tiny yellow bits? Those are the flowers and they are deliciously fragrant.  It&#8217;s a hemiparasitic plant which means that it does its own photosynthesis but it gets water and nutrients from the host plant.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-476\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4674-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4674.jpg 1024w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4674-300x225.jpg 300w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4674-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" /></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p>Aside from ubiquitous Yucca brevifolia the creosote bush, Larrea tridentata, is one of the most common shrubs here.  It&#8217;s reminiscent of Scotch broom and a tiny-leaved Ceanothus at once.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-477\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4678-e1518728802213-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"768\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4678-e1518728802213.jpg 768w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4678-e1518728802213-225x300.jpg 225w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\" /></p>\n<p>For some reason I like this growth habit.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-478\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4677-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4677.jpg 1024w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4677-300x225.jpg 300w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4677-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" /></p>\n<p>Neato black stripes on many of its branches.  Are those scars? Growth &#8220;rings&#8221;? Is this thing really that old? I have no idea but I like it.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-479\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4679-e1518729073483-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"768\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4679-e1518729073483.jpg 768w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4679-e1518729073483-225x300.jpg 225w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\" /></p>\n<p>Pinus monophylla made an appearance.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-480\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4713-e1518729279278-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"768\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4713-e1518729279278.jpg 768w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4713-e1518729279278-225x300.jpg 225w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\" /></p>\n<p>And there was quite a bit of Quercus cornelius-mulleri, a very satisfying evergreen oak which I found was generally shrubby with good form., often growing in very rocky areas.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-481\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4718-e1518729450282-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"768\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4718-e1518729450282.jpg 768w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4718-e1518729450282-225x300.jpg 225w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\" /></p>\n<p>I&#8217;m going to let the rest of this post be a photo essay and not bother you with any more words.</p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-482\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4687-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4687.jpg 1024w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4687-300x225.jpg 300w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4687-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" /></p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-483\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4689-e1518729572649-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"768\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4689-e1518729572649.jpg 768w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4689-e1518729572649-225x300.jpg 225w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\" /></p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-484\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4692-e1518729609699-768x1024.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"768\" height=\"1024\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4692-e1518729609699.jpg 768w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4692-e1518729609699-225x300.jpg 225w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 768px) 100vw, 768px\" /></p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-485\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4696-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4696.jpg 1024w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4696-300x225.jpg 300w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4696-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" /></p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-486\" src=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4697-1024x768.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"1024\" height=\"768\" srcset=\"https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4697.jpg 1024w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4697-300x225.jpg 300w, https://plant-collage.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/02/IMG_4697-768x576.jpg 768w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 1024px) 100vw, 1024px\" /></p>\n<p><img class=\"aligncenter size-large wp-image-487\" src=\"https://pla